[32m+[m[32m# 06 – Data Lake and Query Layer (S3 + Athena)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis stage introduces a scalable analytics layer using Amazon S3 and Amazon Athena.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhile DynamoDB serves as the operational data store for real-time ingestion, Amazon S3 is used as a data lake for long-term storage and analytical workloads.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 6.1 Amazon S3 (Data Lake)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mDynamoDB data was initially exported to Amazon S3 to validate archival and data lake integration capabilities.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis confirmed that operational telemetry data can be offloaded for long-term storage.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHowever, the native export format (Amazon Ion) is not optimised for analytics workloads and can lead to parsing issues when queried using Athena.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Limitation of DynamoDB Export[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe exported dataset uses Amazon Ion format, which introduces:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* Nested structures[m
[32m+[m[32m* Type annotations (e.g. `N`, `S`)[m
[32m+[m[32m* Compatibility challenges with Athena queries[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAs a result, this format is suitable for archival purposes but not ideal for analytics or dashboarding.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Analytics Dataset (Lambda → S3)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mTo address this limitation, the Lambda function was extended to write a separate, flattened JSON dataset directly to S3.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mEach telemetry event is transformed into an analytics-friendly structure before being stored.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample structure:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```json[m
[32m+[m[32m{[m
[32m+[m[32m  "device_id": "raspberry-pi-edge-gateway",[m
[32m+[m[32m  "timestamp": "2026-05-04T12:44:44Z",[m
[32m+[m[32m  "temperature_c": 28.84,[m
[32m+[m[32m  "co_raw": 279,[m
[32m+[m[32m  "light_raw": 36,[m
[32m+[m[32m  "sound_raw": 12,[m
[32m+[m[32m  "light_state": "dark",[m
[32m+[m[32m  "sound_event": false[m
[32m+[m[32m}[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32m### Partitioning Strategy[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mData is stored using a date-based partitioning scheme:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```text[m
[32m+[m[32manalytics/year=YYYY/month=MM/day=DD/[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis improves query performance and reduces cost when using Athena.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 6.2 Data Flow[m
[32m+[m[32mLambda → S3 → Athena → QuickSight[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis pipeline enables:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* Serverless querying using Athena[m
[32m+[m[32m* Efficient access to large datasets[m
[32m+[m[32m* Integration with visualisation tools[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 6.3 Analytics Data Strategy[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mTwo data paths are maintained:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* DynamoDB – Operational store for real-time ingestion and recent telemetry access[m
[32m+[m[32m* S3 (JSON) – Analytics store for Athena and QuickSight[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis separation ensures:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* Low-latency access for operational workloads[m
[32m+[m[32m* Scalable and cost-efficient storage for analytics[m
[32m+[m[32m* Clean data structures optimised for querying[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 6.4 Athena Query Layer[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAmazon Athena is used to query telemetry data stored in S3 using standard SQL.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mKey capabilities include:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m* Serverless querying (no infrastructure required)[m
[32m+[m[32m* Direct integration with S3[m
[32m+[m[32m* Seamless connection to QuickSight[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAthena enables efficient analysis of telemetry data without impacting the operational DynamoDB workload.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mNotes[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mDue to the architecture (S3 → Athena), this layer supports near-real-time analytics rather than real-time processing. Data availability depends on S3 write timing and Athena query execution.[m
